\size large
\color blue
Exercise 6.6.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset VSpace defskip
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Find and identify all critical points of
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
f(x,y)=3x^{2}y+4xy^{2}+xy.
\]

\end_inset

Determine whether they are the locations of local maxima, minima, or saddle
 points.
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset VSpace bigskip
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\family sans
\series bold
\size large
\color black
Solution.
 
\family default
\series default
\size default
\color inherit
Differentiating, we have 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\D f(x,y) & = & \begin{bmatrix}\part{f(x,y)}x & \part{f(x,y)}y\end{bmatrix}\\
 & = & \begin{bmatrix}6xy+4y^{2}+y & 2x^{2}+8xy+x\end{bmatrix},
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

which equals 
\begin_inset Formula $\o$
\end_inset

 at 
\begin_inset Formula $(x,y)=\begin{cases}
(0,0)\\
\left(0,-\frac{1}{4}\right)\\
\left(\frac{1}{3},0\right)\\
\left(-\frac{1}{9},-\frac{1}{12}\right)
\end{cases}.$
\end_inset

 Thus our Hessian is
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\D^{2}f(x,y)=\begin{bmatrix}6y & 6x+8y+1\\
6x+8y+1 & 8x
\end{bmatrix},
\]

\end_inset

which evaluates to a negative definite matrix only for 
\begin_inset Formula $(x,y)=\left(-\frac{1}{9},-\frac{1}{12}\right)$
\end_inset

, so 
\begin_inset Formula $(x,y)=\left(-\frac{1}{9},-\frac{1}{12}\right)$
\end_inset

 is a local maximum.
 For the points 
\begin_inset Formula $(x,y)=\begin{cases}
(0,0)\\
\left(0,-\frac{1}{4}\right)\\
\left(\frac{1}{3},0\right)
\end{cases},$
\end_inset

 the Hessian is neither positive nor negative definite, so they are saddle
 points.
 
\begin_inset Formula $\qed$
\end_inset


\begin_inset VSpace bigskip
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset VSpace bigskip
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Box Shaded
position "t"
hor_pos "c"
has_inner_box 1
inner_pos "t"
use_parbox 0
use_makebox 0
width "100col%"
special "none"
height "1in"
height_special "totalheight"
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\family sans
\series bold
\size large
\color blue
Exercise 6.7.
\family default
\series default
\size default
\color inherit

\begin_inset VSpace defskip
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
An unconstrained quadratic optimization problem is an optimization problem
 with no constraints where the objective function 
\begin_inset Formula $f:\R^{n}\to\R$
\end_inset

 is quadratic, meaning that it can be written in the form
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Formula $\lcr{}{f(\x)=\x\T\A\x-\mathbf{b}\T\x+c,}{(6.17)}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
for some square matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{A}\in\mathrm{M}_{n}(\R)$
\end_inset

 and some vector 
\begin_inset Formula $\b\in\R^{n}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Labeling
\labelwidthstring 00.00.0000
\begin_inset Formula $\l i$
\end_inset

 Prove that for any square matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{A}$
\end_inset

 the matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{Q}=\mathbf{A}\T+\mathbf{A}$
\end_inset

 is symmetric, and 
\begin_inset Formula $\x\T\mathbf{Q}\x=\x\t\mathbf{A}\t\x+\x\t\mathbf{A}\x=2\x\t\mathbf{A}\x$
\end_inset

, so (6.17) is equal to 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Labeling
\labelwidthstring 00.00.0000
\begin_inset Formula $\ $
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $\lcr{}{f(\x)=\frac{1}{2}\x\t\mathbf{Q}\x-\b\t\x+c}{(6.18)}.$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Labeling
\labelwidthstring 00.00.0000
\begin_inset Formula $\ $
\end_inset

 Thus we may always assume that quadratic functions are of the form (6.18)
 with 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{Q}$
\end_inset

 symmetric.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Labeling
\labelwidthstring 00.00.0000
\begin_inset Formula $\l{ii}$
\end_inset

 Prove that any minimizer 
\begin_inset Formula $\x\s$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 is a solution of the equation
\end_layout

\begin_layout Labeling
\labelwidthstring 00.00.0000
\begin_inset Formula $\ $
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $\lcr{}{\mathbf{Q}\t\x\s=\b.}{(6.19)}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Labeling
\labelwidthstring 00.00.0000
\begin_inset Formula $\l{iii}$
\end_inset

 Prove that the quadratic minimization problem (6.17) will have a solution
 if and only if 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{Q}$
\end_inset

 is positive definite, and in that case, the minimizer is the solution of
 the linear system (6.19).
 Explain why this shows that solving the system (6.19) with positive definite
 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{Q}$
\end_inset

 is equivalent to solving the quadratic optimization problem (6.18).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Labeling
\labelwidthstring 00.00.0000
\begin_inset Formula $\ $
\end_inset

 Depending on 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{Q}$
\end_inset

, the best way to solve the linear system (6.19) is often to use optimization
 algorithms on the quadratic problem (6.17) instead of using linear solvers
 on (6.19).
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset VSpace bigskip
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\family sans
\series bold
\size large
\color black
Solution.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Labeling
\labelwidthstring 00.00.0000
\begin_inset Formula $\l i$
\end_inset

 If 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{A}$
\end_inset

 is square, then 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{A}\t+\mathbf{A}$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\begin{bmatrix}a_{11} & \cdots & a_{1n}\\
\vdots & \ddots & \vdots\\
a_{n1} & \cdots & a_{nn}
\end{bmatrix}+\begin{bmatrix}a_{11} & \cdots & a_{n1}\\
\vdots & \ddots & \vdots\\
a_{1n} & \cdots & a_{nn}
\end{bmatrix} & = & \begin{bmatrix}2\cdot a_{11} & \cdots & a_{1n}+a_{n1}\\
\vdots & \ddots & \vdots\\
a_{n1}+a_{1n} & \cdots & 2\cdot a_{nn}
\end{bmatrix}\\
 & = & \begin{bmatrix}2\cdot a_{11} & \cdots & a_{1n}+a_{n1}\\
\vdots & \ddots & \vdots\\
a_{1n}+a_{1n} & \cdots & 2\cdot a_{nn}
\end{bmatrix},
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

so 
\begin_inset Formula $(\mathbf{A}\t+\mathbf{A})\t$
\end_inset

 is
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\begin{bmatrix}2\cdot a_{11} & \cdots & a_{1n}+a_{n1}\\
\vdots & \ddots & \vdots\\
a_{1n}+a_{1n} & \cdots & 2\cdot a_{nn}
\end{bmatrix},
\]

\end_inset

which is itself, so it is symmetric.
 So, we have that
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\x\t\mathbf{Q}\x & = & \x\t(\mathbf{A}\t+\mathbf{A})\x\\
 & = & \x\t\mathbf{A}\t\x+\x\t\mathbf{A}\x\\
 & = & \x\t\mathbf{A}\x+\x\t\mathbf{A}\x\\
 & = & 2\cdot\x\t\mathbf{A}\x.
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

So, we can see that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\x\T\mathbf{A}\x-\mathbf{b}\T\x+c & = & \frac{1}{2}\cdot\left(2\cdot\x\T\mathbf{A}\x\right)-\mathbf{b}\T\x+c\\
 & = & \frac{1}{2}\cdot\left(\x\t\mathbf{A}\x+\x\t\mathbf{A}\x\right)-\b\t\x+c\\
 & = & \frac{1}{2}\cdot\left(\x\t\mathbf{A}\t\x+\x\t\mathbf{A}\x\right)-\b\t\x+c\\
 & = & \x\t(\mathbf{A}\t+\mathbf{A})\x\\
 & = & \frac{1}{2}\cdot\x\t\mathbf{Q}\x-\b\t\x+c.
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $\qed$
\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Labeling
\labelwidthstring 00.00.0000
\begin_inset Formula $\l{ii}$
\end_inset

 This is a direct corollary of the FONC—
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{Q}\t\x\s=\b$
\end_inset

 because 
\begin_inset Formula $f\pr(\x)=\mathbf{Q}\t\x-\b$
\end_inset

.
\begin_inset Formula $\qed$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Labeling
\labelwidthstring 00.00.0000
\begin_inset Formula $\l{iii}$
\end_inset

 If 
\begin_inset Formula $Q$
\end_inset

 PSD, then 
\begin_inset Formula $f\ppr(\x)>0$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $\forall\x\in\r^{n}$
\end_inset

.
 By (6.19) and the fact that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{Q}$
\end_inset

 is invertible, we know that 
\begin_inset Formula $\x\s=\mathbf{Q}^{-1}\b$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $\x\s$
\end_inset

 is the value where 
\begin_inset Formula $f\pr(\x\s)=0$
\end_inset

.
 So, by SOSC, 
\begin_inset Formula $\x\s$
\end_inset

 is a 
\emph on
unique
\emph default
 minimizer of 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $\x\s$
\end_inset

 is the unique minimizer, then by SONC we know that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{Q}$
\end_inset

 is PSD and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{Q}\t\x\s=\b$
\end_inset

.
 If 
\series bold

\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{Q}$
\end_inset


\series default
 has at least one e-value equal to zero, then 
\begin_inset Formula $\x\s$
\end_inset

 is 
\emph on
not
\emph default
 unique, so 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{Q}$
\end_inset

 
\emph on
must
\emph default
 be positive definite.
 
\begin_inset Formula $\qed$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset VSpace bigskip
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset VSpace bigskip
\end_inset


\end_layout

