\begin_layout Plain Layout

\family sans
\series bold
\size large
\color blue
Exercise 6.11.
\family default
\series default
\size default
\color inherit

\begin_inset VSpace defskip
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Consider a quadratic function 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x)=ax^{2}+bx+c$
\end_inset

, here 
\begin_inset Formula $a>0$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $b,c\in\R$
\end_inset

.
 Show that for any initial guess 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{0}\in\R$
\end_inset

, one iteration of Newton's method lands at the unique minimizer of 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset VSpace bigskip
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\family sans
\series bold
\size large
\color black
Solution.
 
\family default
\series default
\size default
\color inherit

\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 has a minimum at 
\begin_inset Formula $x=-\frac{b}{2a}$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x)=a\cdot\left(x+\frac{b}{2a}\right)^{2}-a\cdot\left(\frac{b}{2a}\right)^{2},$
\end_inset

 so the Newton's method always yields 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
x_{1} & = & x_{0}-\frac{f\pr(x_{0})}{f\ppr(x_{0}}\\
 & = & x_{0}-\frac{2ax_{0}+b}{2a}\\
 & = & -\frac{b}{2a}.
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $\qed$
\end_inset


\begin_inset VSpace bigskip
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset VSpace bigskip
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Box Shaded
position "t"
hor_pos "c"
has_inner_box 1
inner_pos "t"
use_parbox 0
use_makebox 0
width "100col%"
special "none"
height "1in"
height_special "totalheight"
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\family sans
\series bold
\size large
\color blue
Exercise 6.15.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset VSpace defskip
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Code up (in Python/NumPy) the secant method for finding a minimizer of a
 function.
 Your code should accept two initial guesses 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{0}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{1}$
\end_inset

, a desired level of accuracy 
\begin_inset Formula $\ep$
\end_inset

, and a callable function 
\begin_inset Formula $f\pr(x)$
\end_inset

.
 It should return an approximation to a minimizer of 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

, provided the algorithm converges for the initial conditions.
 For the stopping criterion, use 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|x_{k+1}-x_{k}\right|<\left|x_{k}\right|\varepsilon$
\end_inset

.
 Be sure your code has methods for identifying and handling cases where
 the sequence does not converge.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset VSpace defskip
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Write your code in a notebook and test it with the function 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x)=x^{4}-14x^{3}+60x^{2}+70x$
\end_inset

 and initial guess 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{0}=0$
\end_inset

.
 Plot the function and the points and function values at each iteration
 in an appropriate graph.
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset VSpace bigskip
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\family sans
\series bold
\size large
\color black
Solution.
 
\end_layout

